06:46.527 --> 06:49.028
- Joe Cocker.
- Why?

06:49.030 --> 06:51.197
Yet again with the questions.

06:51.199 --> 06:53.735
Let's review, shall we?
I ask, you answer.

06:56.104 --> 06:57.937
Where are you from?

06:59.874 --> 07:01.807
- Minnesota.
- Minnesota.

07:01.809 --> 07:03.843
There we go. That
wasn't that hard.

07:03.845 --> 07:07.614
- And when were you infected?
- It was the end of October.

07:08.049 --> 07:09.583
What?

07:10.617 --> 07:12.018
It was the end of October?

07:12.020 --> 07:14.819
We were putting up
Halloween decorations.

07:14.821 --> 07:16.124
You're certain?

07:18.992 --> 07:20.560
You're sure about that?

07:21.194 --> 07:22.696
<b></font></b> Yeah.

07:29.803 --> 07:31.171
Get me the Minnesota file.

07:32.606 --> 07:34.326
Bring up all that data
we have on Minnesota.

07:34.540 --> 07:36.673
And tell Morgan to keep
pushing him on that.

07:36.675 --> 07:38.575
- On it.
- What are his vitals?

07:38.577 --> 07:39.880
Let me check.

07:41.148 --> 07:43.081
Okay, and who bit you?

07:46.886 --> 07:50.587
Geographically possible.
Look, November, December.

07:50.589 --> 07:51.822
It's not even close.

07:51.824 --> 07:53.759
This is one of the
earliest we've spoken to.

07:55.961 --> 07:58.062
Come on, Morgan,
give me what I need.

07:58.064 --> 07:59.696
Tell me about the attack today?

07:59.698 --> 08:02.666
We couldn't believe our luck
when your soldiers showed up.

08:02.668 --> 08:04.868
The feeling I felt in my gut...

08:04.870 --> 08:06.670
- You mean the burn?
- What?

08:06.672 --> 08:08.939
You mean the burn, the
burn to commit violence,

08:08.941 --> 08:11.175
to be violent, to tear
someone's head off.

08:11.177 --> 08:14.244
To rip someone's teeth out.
You're talking about the burn?

08:14.246 --> 08:17.181
Yeah, I know about
the burn, Joe.

08:17.183 --> 08:18.950
We're not that
different, me and you.

08:21.019 --> 08:22.985
Like lust.

08:22.987 --> 08:25.188
I understand you, buddy.

08:25.190 --> 08:26.691
And I wanna help you.

08:29.127 --> 08:30.929
Joe.

08:32.197 --> 08:34.263
So how many of you
were traveling today?

08:34.265 --> 08:37.166
- 200, 250.
- 250? That's a lot.

08:37.168 --> 08:39.102
We ripped your soldiers apart.

08:39.104 --> 08:41.037
And if it weren't
for these chains...

08:41.039 --> 08:43.640
Hey, hey, hey, have you ever
heard of Daniel Burnham?

08:44.943 --> 08:47.110
So, Daniel Burnham
was an architect.

08:47.112 --> 08:48.877
This brilliant architect. Okay?

08:48.879 --> 08:51.746
He designed all these famous
buildings across the United States

08:51.748 --> 08:54.350
including, actually the
first skyscraper in Chicago

08:54.352 --> 08:57.286
and that amazing building
in New York City,

08:57.288 --> 09:02.924
the Flatiron. Anyway, his
real passion was wine.

09:02.926 --> 09:05.861
Danny Burnham shipped his
around the world, twice,

09:05.863 --> 09:09.798
on these slow freighters.
So, sometimes the wine

09:09.800 --> 09:14.102
would take years, and years,
and years to come back to him.

09:14.104 --> 09:17.105
Anyway, one day, me and my wife,

09:17.107 --> 09:19.975
we're in this really beautiful building
that Burnham designed in like,

09:19.977 --> 09:22.776
nineteen hundred and something.

09:22.778 --> 09:27.681
And we come across five
old, beautiful, dusty cases

09:27.683 --> 09:30.184
of Daniel Burnham's wine.
The point is,

09:30.186 --> 09:34.321
whenever Daniel Burnham opened a bottle
of his wine amongst his buddies,

09:34.323 --> 09:36.403
he would read them the long
list of all the countries

09:36.427 --> 09:38.759
that each specific
bottle had traveled,

09:38.761 --> 09:42.363
so whenever they drank it they
knew it wasn't just a sip

09:42.365 --> 09:45.266
of beautiful wine,

09:45.268 --> 09:47.736
this was a trip around
the motherfucking world.

09:51.040 --> 09:55.808
This wine is my only
connection to the past, Joe.

09:55.810 --> 09:57.779
To the world as it was.

09:58.847 --> 10:01.215
Remember that.

10:01.217 --> 10:05.187
You know, Joe, I've forgotten
what fresh air feels like.

10:06.888 --> 10:09.856
And sunlight. I hate this place.

10:09.858 --> 10:11.424
I hate seeing you
people in pain.

10:11.426 --> 10:13.126
I hate not being
able to help you,

10:13.128 --> 10:17.864
but I wanna understand you, Joe.
I do.

10:17.866 --> 10:19.832
<b></b> <i>Looks like we're making
real progress in there.</i>

10:19.834 --> 10:21.334
Shit.

10:21.336 --> 10:23.303
Hey, hey, hey, hey. Take it easy.
Take it easy.

10:23.305 --> 10:25.438
Don't make me. Come on, man.
Take it easy.

10:25.440 --> 10:26.939
I wanna help you.

10:29.444 --> 10:31.910
Listen to me. Listen to me.
Listen to me!

10:31.912 --> 10:33.714
What is wrong with you?

10:35.283 --> 10:37.417
I'm trying to make progress in there.
What is it with this dude?

10:37.419 --> 10:39.351
- Are you all right?
- No. Yeah. I'm fine.

10:39.353 --> 10:42.187
- What's he keep saying in there?
- For me to go fuck myself.

10:42.189 --> 10:43.989
<b></b> Tell him we'd all
do that if we could.

10:43.991 --> 10:45.791
<b></font></b> Why are you coddling
that son of a bitch?

10:45.793 --> 10:47.459
Please, Colonel.

10:47.461 --> 10:49.096
When was the last Halloween?

10:50.164 --> 10:51.863
Last October.

10:51.865 --> 10:53.332
No, that we celebrated.

10:53.334 --> 10:55.970
Oh. Um, a year and a half ago.

10:57.238 --> 10:59.173
My Tommy was Spiderman.

11:00.940 --> 11:03.141
- I want some answers.
- Back off, Colonel.

11:03.143 --> 11:05.479
- What is the problem?
- Colonel, there is no problem.

11:05.713 --> 11:07.633
I just need the subject to calm down.
That's all.

11:07.657 --> 11:09.414
Bullshit. Get him back inside

11:09.416 --> 11:12.049
and show that monster who's
in charge, or I will.

11:12.051 --> 11:14.320
- That's enough, Colonel.
- This guy, man.

11:17.323 --> 11:18.889
You're damn right it is.

11:20.793 --> 11:22.026
- What's he doing?
- Colonel!

11:22.028 --> 11:23.194
- Hey! Hey!
- What?

11:28.067 --> 11:30.101
Now, he looks pretty
damn calm to me.

11:30.103 --> 11:31.383
What the fuck is wrong with you?

11:31.407 --> 11:32.869
Are you out of
your goddamn mind?

11:32.871 --> 11:35.206
- He was wasting our time.
- He was from Minnesota.

11:35.208 --> 11:36.806
He was infected Halloween night,

11:36.808 --> 11:38.648
that predates any previous
record of infection.

11:38.672 --> 11:41.445
He might, he just might, have
been a link to Patient Zero.

11:41.447 --> 11:43.514
<b><font face="Rockwell" color="#D900D9">Get your hands off me.

11:43.516 --> 11:45.284
You're gonna shoot me, Colonel?

11:47.986 --> 11:50.989
There are a million
more just like him.

11:51.456 --> 11:53.156
What the...

11:53.158 --> 11:55.358
Put the fucking wine away.
Clean up this shit.

11:55.360 --> 11:57.360
- You're an asshole.
- Let's bring in the next one.

11:57.384 --> 12:00.230
You were born an asshole, and you
will fucking die an asshole.

12:00.232 --> 12:05.502
I hate this fucking place!

12:05.504 --> 12:07.437
You overstep your
authority like that again

12:07.439 --> 12:09.172
and I'll have you
stripped of your command.

12:09.174 --> 12:12.074
- My orders...
- Your orders are to protect

12:12.076 --> 12:15.311
my laboratory. What we do
here is scientific research,

12:15.313 --> 12:18.548
not executions. You shot
him to get even with me.

12:18.550 --> 12:20.482
Don't even think
about denying it.

12:20.484 --> 12:22.985
You're upset that I put you down
and spoke to you like a child.

12:22.987 --> 12:25.454
But I have no choice when you
continue to act like a child.

12:25.456 --> 12:27.323
I get that you're frustrated,

12:27.325 --> 12:30.159
that you're posted to a scientific
operation and not a military one.

12:30.161 --> 12:33.962
I understand, but you do
something like that again

12:33.964 --> 12:36.532
and I promise you will rue
the day that we ever met,

12:36.534 --> 12:39.069
if you don't already.
Are we clear, Colonel?

12:47.345 --> 12:49.212
I'll take that as a yes.

12:55.852 --> 12:58.486
He was traveling in a much
larger pack than normal today.

12:58.488 --> 13:00.188
250, he said, you know.

13:00.190 --> 13:02.030
A wolf-pack stays big
enough to hunt as a team,

13:02.054 --> 13:03.591
but small enough
to feed everybody.

13:03.593 --> 13:06.561
And 250 is not a pack,
it's a goddamn army.

13:06.563 --> 13:08.563
I'd like you to calm down.
Take a couple of these.

13:08.565 --> 13:11.532
No! No! I cannot
take any more pills.

13:11.534 --> 13:13.401
It's driving me insane.

13:13.403 --> 13:16.537
I keep having these nightmares.
These vivid flashbacks.

13:16.539 --> 13:18.341
Stay still, I'm gonna
take your pulse.

13:19.908 --> 13:22.510
Yes, flashbacks, okay. Go on.

13:22.512 --> 13:26.980
I can hear her scream,
but I can't, I just... <b></b>

13:26.982 --> 13:28.515
I can't reach her, you know.

13:28.517 --> 13:31.453
- Stop torturing yourself.
- That's all I do. Torture myself.

13:32.921 --> 13:34.223
Stop.

13:37.493 --> 13:39.559
You know Janet and
I had this thing.

13:39.561 --> 13:41.428
We never liked saying
goodbye to each other

13:41.430 --> 13:43.132
because it sounds so permanent.

13:44.533 --> 13:46.566
So instead of saying goodbye,

13:46.568 --> 13:49.671
we would pick a random
topic from the alphabet.

13:50.972 --> 13:53.339
And we would recycle
through all 26 letters

13:53.341 --> 13:55.910
over and over again, but we
would never say the words,

13:57.011 --> 13:59.013
- "Goodbye."
- That's cute.

13:59.380 --> 14:00.649
Yeah.

14:02.417 --> 14:04.018
Yeah, that's cute.

14:06.120 --> 14:08.923
Don't you miss that? Don't
you miss being cute?

14:10.425 --> 14:14.195
Being human? Hell, yeah.

14:17.498 --> 14:19.132
You're fine.

15:32.237 --> 15:33.606
Hope you're being safe.

15:34.205 --> 15:35.639
Excuse me.

15:35.641 --> 15:38.474
Is it advisable to consort with
someone who's been bitten,

15:38.476 --> 15:40.543
from a scientific perspective?

15:40.545 --> 15:42.411
I have no idea what
you're talking about.

15:42.413 --> 15:45.147
Or maybe this is some
perverse line of research.

15:45.149 --> 15:47.619
I don't know. You tell me.

15:48.720 --> 15:51.556
- Oh, my God. That's it.
- What?

15:54.592 --> 15:57.795
You're upset that I care
for Morgan, aren't you?

